RT @lrnchat: #lrnchat today at 11:30ET, 4:30BT -- todays topic? Learning Traps. (I'll be taking part so pardon the tweets) #lrnchat
Chris Jobling, university teacher, Swansea UK. Interested in improving the learning experiences of our students. #lrnchat
Q0) Learned in #plenk2010 that there is a role for a discussion board. #lrnchat
Q1) How to sabotage learning? Assume that academics who's promotion depends on measured research outputs is interested in teaching. #lrnchat
Q1) Your job is to prepare 20 lectures, give them and set an exam. If learning doesn't happen - blame the students. #lrnchat
@chris_hall: finally emerging from the shadows! ... what do you think? #lrnchat
RT @lrnchat: Q2) What are some common learning traps we find ourselves and our learners in? #lrnchat
Q2) I have to admit to have taught a few courses where I "prepared 20 lectures, gave them, and set an exam."  12 step plan please! #lrnchat
Q2) The road to learning traps is paved with good intentions. #lrnchat
RT @mrch0mp3rs: Defining "learning trap" = stuff we know to avoid, but end up doing anyway. < Yes! #lrnchat
Q2) The inertia trap: "This is how I learned this so it must be good enough for you!" #lrnchat
RT @lrnchat: Q3) What can we do to avoid falling into these learning traps? #lrnchat
Q3) Personally, I'd be a better teacher if I'd learned a bit about how learners learn. Self-taught is not necessarily well taught. #lrnchat
RT @techherding: Q3) Ask two questions post-mortem.  "What went well?" "What could go better?"  < I'll try that, thanks! #lrnchat
Q3) so reflection? Mirror, mirror on the wall, was that any good at all? #lrnchat
RT @lrnchat: Q4) How do we build a "mindfulness" of the learning traps we fall into? How do stay open to change? #lrnchat
Q4) "To be a good teacher you have to be a lifelong learner." Don't know who said that but it might have been heard in #plenk2010. #lrnchat
Q4) "Nobody's perfect" (Some Like it Hot, RIP Tony!) #lrnchat
